266":"1266","1199":"1199","about 1244":"about 1244","about 1266":"about 1266","after 1275":"after 1275","about 1220":"about 1220","1308":"1308","1229":"1229","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Wentworth, Yorkshire, England":"Wentworth, Yorkshire, England","Wentworth Woodhouse, Yorkshire, England":"Wentworth Woodhouse, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wentworth","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Wentworth in Yorkshire. The placename probably derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wintra</i> + Old English <i>worth</i> ‘enclosure’.","habitational name from Wentworth in Cambridgeshire, which has the same etymology as the placename in 1 above."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":4,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":39,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Wentworth was born about 1220, in Wentworth Woodhouse, Yorkshire, England, his father, William Wentworth, was 23 and his mother, Mrs William Wodehouse, was 22. He married Emma de Woodhouse. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died after 1275, in Wentworth, Yorkshire, England."},"et":{"about 1220–after 1275":"umbes 1220–pärast 1275","1220–1275":"1220–1275","1229–Female":"1229–Surnud","1225–1266":"1225–1266","1244–1308":"1244–1308","1199–1275":"1199–1275","1200–Female":"1200–Surnud","1275":"1275","1220":"1220","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1244":"1244","1266":"1266","1199":"1199","about 1244":"umbes 1244","about 1266":"umbes 1266","after 1275":"pärast 1275","about 1220":"umbes 1220","1308":"1308","1229":"1229","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Wentworth, Yorkshire, England":"Wentworth, Yorkshire, England","Wentworth Woodhouse, Yorkshire, England":"Wentworth Woodhouse, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1220–after 1275":"noin 1220–1275 jälkeen","1220–1275":"1220–1275","1229–Female":"1229–Kuollut","1225–1266":"1225–1266","1244–1308":"1244–1308","1199–1275":"1199–1275","1200–Female":"1200–Kuollut","1275":"1275","1220":"1220","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1244":"1244","1266":"1266","1199":"1199","about 1244":"noin 1244","about 1266":"noin 1266","after 1275":"1275 jälkeen","about 1220":"noin 1220","1308":"1308","1229":"1229","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Wentworth, Yorkshire, England":"Wentworth, Yorkshire, England","Wentworth Woodhouse, Yorkshir